paper/review/round1/citations.md-4-   **LOCATION:** Abstract, p. 1, “roughly a third of American megagiving in 2025”; Introduction, p. 1, “by the Indiana University Lilly Family School of Philanthropy’s accounting, about a third of every megagift in America that year”; `references.bib`, `cnbc2025scott`.  
paper/review/round1/citations.md:5:   **Problem:** The underlying statistic is about dollars, not the number of gifts: $6.65 billion of Scott's contributions represented about one-third of the $19.2 billion *value* of 2025 megagifts. The current wording “a third of every megagift” is scope-inaccurate. More seriously, the cited December 2025 CNBC story predates Giving USA 2026 and contains neither the $19.2 billion denominator nor the one-third comparison; it discusses Scott's $7.17 billion and Giving USA's *2024 total-giving* figure. Its BibTeX is also misattributed: the [CNBC publisher page](https://www.cnbc.com/2025/12/13/mackenzie-scott-revealed-her-total-charitable-donations-for-2025.html) names Tom Huddleston Jr., not Lorie Konish, and its title is “MacKenzie Scott announced another $7.1 billion in 2025 charitable donations—she's now given away $26.3 billion since 2019.” The one-third statistic appears in contemporaneous 2026 reporting based on Giving USA/Lilly data, including [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/06/25/mackenzie-scott-largest-megadonor-2025-7-billion-donations-giving-usa-iu-report/) and the [Associated Press/Chronicle of Philanthropy](https://apnews.com/article/giving-usa-report-philanthropy-2025-8363b76bc8cf854f6865c31129e8a4b1); the [Giving USA release](https://givingusa.org/giving-usa-charitable-giving-rose-to-617-20-billion-in-2025-surpassing-the-600-billion-mark-for-the-first-time/) verifies the distinct $617.20 billion total-giving figure and the report's formal title. This is the same class of source/claim mismatch that the project previously corrected.  
paper/review/round1/citations.md-6-   **Concrete fix:** Replace the sentence with, for example, “Scott's $6.65 billion in qualifying contributions represented about one-third of the $19.2 billion value of U.S. megagifts in 2025,” and cite a source that actually states those figures (or give the exact Giving USA 2026 page/table). Remove CNBC from this claim. If CNBC remains for the $7.17 billion annual total, correct its author and title. Preserve the distinction between megagift value and total charitable giving.
