paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1240-   149	## Where it comes from
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1241-   150	
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1242:   151	@tbl-cause decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper's central fact: the global health and development slice — `{python} F["abroad_share_1"]` of dollars — contributes `{python} F["gh_share"]` of estimated QALYs, at a realized cost of about $10,000 per QALY against $350,000–$450,000 for the large U.S. buckets. The 1,200-fold spread in realized cost-effectiveness within a single donor's portfolio restates, in one column, the central empirical claim of the effective-altruism literature: the cheapest health in the world is not bought where most philanthropic dollars are spent.
