paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1426-     6	MacKenzie Scott has disclosed $26.39 billion in gifts to more than 2,500 organizations since 2019 — roughly a third of American megagiving in 2025 — yet almost
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1427-     7	none of it is denominated in outcomes. This paper prices the entire portfolio in
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1428:     8	quality-adjusted life-years. A Monte Carlo model allocates dollars across 14 intervention archetypes using Scott’s own gift-level database, imputes the undisclosed third
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1429-     9	from recipients’ pre-gift IRS 990 revenue, assigns each archetype a cost-per-QALY
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1430-    10	anchor from published causal estimates, and shrinks every effect toward zero in
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1431-    11	proportion to the causal credibility of its evidence. The best-guess estimate is a
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1432-    12	median of roughly 202,000 QALYs (90% interval 94,000–419,000), a blended $150,000
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1433-    13	per QALY, and a benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 at the U.S. government’s value per QALY.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1434-    14	Three findings follow. First, impact is geographically concentrated: the 4.8% of
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1435:    15	dollars funding health and development delivered outside the United States produces
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1436-    16	69% of estimated health impact. Second, gift size scales with recipient size to only
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1437-    17	the 0.41 power — a 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more money. Third,
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1438-    18	the answer is dominated by evidence philosophy rather than arithmetic: restricting to
--
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1468-    48	evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1469-    49	The paper makes four contributions. It provides, to my knowledge, the first portfolio-level
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1470-    50	cost-effectiveness estimate for a major philanthropist: a best-guess median of 202,000 QALYs
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1471:    51	from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in 2026 dollars), a blended $150,067 per QALY, and a
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1472-    52	benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 at the U.S. government’s value per QALY (U.S. Department of Health
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1473-    53	and Human Services, Office of the Assistant Secretary for Planning and Evaluation 2026). It
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1474:    54	documents extreme geographic concentration of modeled impact: the 4.8% of dollars funding
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1475-    55	global health and development delivered outside the United States accounts for 69.1% of estimated
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1476-    56	health impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the gift data itself: across 1,313 disclosed
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1477-    57	gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift revenue to the power 0.41 (R² 0.37) —
