paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1501-    81	2.2 Allocation across causes
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1502:    82	Scott publishes no aggregate dollars-by-cause breakdown, but she publishes better: a gift-level
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1503-    83	database listing every recipient organization, its self-reported focus areas, and — for 2,035 of 2,711
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1504-    84	gifts ($17.46B, about two-thirds of the nominal total) — the dollar amount. Each organization’s
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1505:    85	dollars are split equally across its focus areas; the database’s 53 areas map onto the model’s 14
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1506-    86	intervention archetypes under a documented, sync-tested crosswalk.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1507-    87	The undisclosed third is imputed rather than dropped. Because the essays give each year’s
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1508-    88	total, the undisclosed residual per period is a known dollar amount; it is distributed across that
--
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1517-    97	representative.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1518-    98	
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1519-    99	2.3 Delivery geography
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1520:   100	Each organization reports service locations. Weighting disclosed dollars by the share of an
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1521:   101	organization’s locations outside the United States, an estimated 20% of disclosed dollars ($3.57
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1522-   102	billion of $17.46B) goes to organizations serving abroad, led by environment, health, and funding
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1523:   103	intermediaries. The model prices geography through a single channel: health-relevant dollars
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1524-   104	route to a global-health archetype in proportion to the recipient’s non-U.S. service share, because
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1525-   105	global health delivery is the one category with a published cost-per-QALY evidence base an
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1526:   106	order of magnitude below U.S. anchors. Education and climate dollars keep their U.S.-study
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1527-   107	anchors wherever they are delivered; if geography changes their effectiveness, the model does not
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1528-   108	capture it.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1529-   109	The coarsest geographic field is the bare label “global.” An audit of the 50 largest organizations
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1530:   110	reporting only that label — 87% of that bucket’s dollars — replaced the blanket assumption of
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1531-   111	fully-abroad delivery with fractions taken from each organization’s own filings and program reports,
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1532-   112	independently verified by a second model family, with per-organization sources committed to the
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1533-   113	repository. Many “global” organizations operate substantially in the United States: Planned
