paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1571-   151	At the best-guess defaults (100,000 draws), the portfolio produces a median of 201,923 QALYs,
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1572-   152	with a 90% interval of 94,000 to 419,000 and a mean of 222,060. The blended cost-effectiveness
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1573:   153	— dollars given over QALYs produced, at the median — is $150,067 per QALY. Monetized at
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1574-   154	the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services’ value per QALY, the health alone repays
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1575-   155	the giving 4.9 times over (90% interval 2.1–11.0). Figure 1 shows the full distribution.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1576-   156	
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1577-   157	4.1 Where it comes from
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1578-   158	Table 1 decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper’s central fact: the global
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:1579:   159	health and development slice — 4.8% of dollars — contributes 69.1% of estimated QALYs, at a
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1580-   160	realized cost of about $10,000 per QALY against $350,000–$450,000 for the large U.S. buckets.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-1581-   161	The 1,200-fold spread in realized cost-effectiveness within a single donor’s portfolio restates, in
