paper/review/sol/methodology.log:2896:paper/index.qmd:87:The paper makes four contributions. It provides, to my knowledge, the first portfolio-level cost-effectiveness estimate for a major philanthropist: a best-guess median of `{python} F["median_k"]` QALYs from $26.39 billion nominal (`{python} F["giving"]` in 2026 dollars), a blended `{python} F["blended"]` per QALY, and a benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 at the U.S. government's value per QALY [@aspe2026values]. It estimates extreme geographic concentration of impact: the `{python} F["abroad_share_1"]` of dollars funding global health and development delivered outside the United States accounts for `{python} F["gh_share"]` of estimated health impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the gift data itself: across `{python} F["n_cal"]` disclosed gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift revenue to the power `{python} F["elasticity"]` (R² `{python} F["r2"]`) — Scott's giving is far flatter across organization size than proportional. And it demonstrates a working method for auditable, AI-assisted cost-effectiveness modeling: the model was built with a frontier language model, reviewed and corrected in public across eleven revision rounds, audited by two independent model families against primary filings, and ships with versioned parameters, machine-checked citations, and a browser implementation that reruns the full Monte Carlo under any reader's assumptions.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2897-paper/index.qmd:101:The undisclosed third is imputed rather than dropped. Because the essays give each year's total, the undisclosed residual per period is a known dollar amount; it is distributed across that period's undisclosed gifts in proportion to each recipient's pre-gift IRS Form 990 total revenue [@propublica2026], raised to an elasticity fit on the disclosed pairs. Pre-gift means the latest filing strictly before the gift year, since a Scott gift mechanically inflates receipt-year revenue. The fit is a finding in its own right: across `{python} F["n_cal"]` disclosed gift–filing pairs, log gift size rises with log revenue with slope `{python} F["elasticity"]` (R² `{python} F["r2"]`). A 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more money, not 10× more. Fuzzy name-to-EIN matches were audited by a third, smaller model against the live IRS API, with corrections committed as a reviewable overlay. The imputed third moves each cause share by at most about 1.5 percentage points — under the imputation model, the disclosed two-thirds is representative.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2898-paper/index.qmd:111:Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. **Causal credibility** asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock [@cesarini2016wealth] or the ACA Medicaid mortality quasi-experiment [@miller2021medicaid; @sommers2017medicaid] keeps most of its effect; the community-health-center rollout design [@bailey2015war] and similar contested quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only categories are shrunk near zero. **Realization** asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers the studied effect at all — transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of the capacity effects of large unrestricted gifts that the Center for Effective Philanthropy documents for Scott's recipients specifically [@cep2023gifts]. It is one global triangular draw with mode 0.80 on support 0.55–1.10.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2899-paper/index.qmd:113:The two discounts partition the doubt: transportability concerns live only in realization, identification concerns only in credibility, and cost-per-QALY priors are stated conditional on the effect being real and delivered. The tier ordering is the defensible part; the levels are judgment, proposed by a language model and reviewed by the author, and the results section reports the full consequence of disagreeing with them.
--
