paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2918-paper/index.qmd:240:The dominant sensitivity is not a parameter but a philosophy. Restricting credit to randomized evidence collapses the median to `{python} F_rct` QALYs — dominated by the one lottery-randomized bucket — while taking every cited effect at face value raises it to `{python} F_face` (@fig-stance). That 45-fold range exceeds the spread from any distributional parameter, and the gap between the face-value and best-guess estimates is a direct reading of how much of the estimated impact rests on evidence below randomized or strong quasi-experimental identification standards. The Spearman tornado (@fig-tornado) tells the same story within the default stance: the top three drivers are the global-health allocation share, the realization factor, and global-health credibility.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2919-paper/index.qmd:246:The geography audit is the largest data correction the model has absorbed since publication, and its effect is small: recentering the allocation on audited service geographies moved the abroad share from 4.93% to `{python} F["abroad_share"]`, the median from about 205,000 to `{python} F["median"]`, and the blended figure from about $148,000 to `{python} F["blended"]` per QALY. Both allocations ship with the model, the browser version exposes them as a version toggle, and the pre-audit parameters remain pinned at tag `v2026.07.20` (audited: `v2026.07.22`).
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:2920:paper/index.qmd:250:The model reached this state through eleven public revision rounds, and the trajectory is itself evidence about the method. Cross-model review rounds cut the headline from roughly 98,000 to 87,000 QALYs (dollar-vintage normalization, a life-year/QALY conversion made explicit, a re-derived frontier benchmark, one re-attributed citation). Replacing an assumed allocation with the derivation from Scott's own database cut it to roughly 70,000. A reader's correction — health dollars had been priced at U.S. anchors regardless of delivery location — tripled it to roughly 205,000, and the subsequent two-model geography audit settled it at `{python} F["median_k"]`. Every correction is documented in the repository and summarized on the public tool; none was caught by the author unaided, and all but one were caught by models or readers rather than the author.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:2921:paper/index.qmd:260:The credibility tiers and realization distribution are judgment priors with no literature calibration; the ordering is defensible, the levels are not measured, and the stance sweep is the honest bound on their influence. The QALY lens counts only health, so the estimate is a floor on total wellbeing, and the causes where Scott concentrates — education, mobility, equity — are precisely those whose main benefits the lens excludes. Credibility shrinks toward zero but never below it, so the model places no mass on harmful giving. Allocation splits each organization's dollars equally across its focus areas and service locations; both are coarse, and the geography audit covers only the 50 largest "global"-listed organizations. Realization is one global draw, so it cannot vary by cause. Archetype anchors treat heterogeneous organizations as draws from one distribution. Within each cause, delivery regions are priced identically, so the geographic decomposition exposes assumptions rather than measuring regional differences. The undisclosed third of dollars is imputed from a fitted elasticity, not observed. Finally, several anchors rest on a small number of quasi-experimental papers whose external validity to Scott's grantees is exactly what the realization factor is guessing at.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:2922:paper/index.qmd:264:Measured in health, MacKenzie Scott's $26 billion buys a median of about `{python} F["median_k"]` quality-adjusted life-years — several times its cost at the government's own valuation — and most of that health comes from the twentieth of her dollars delivered in low-income countries. The number is a model output under stated priors, not a fact, and the model's most important output is not the point estimate but the machinery around it: explicit evidence weights, a 45-fold stance range that any reader can traverse, versioned corrections, and audits committed as data. Portfolio-scale philanthropy is measurable in outcomes without waiting for donors to publish outcome data — their own gift lists, recipients' tax filings, and the published causal literature suffice — and the same machinery applies to any large giver with comparable gift-level disclosure — or, through the grant listings in public filings, to foundations. The invitation of the interactive version is the paper's real conclusion: disagree with a parameter, move it, and watch what survives.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2923-paper/review/round1/neutrality.md:7:This paper is unusually disciplined for its genre. It contains no policy prescriptions, never argues Scott should give differently, and builds an explicit anti-overreach architecture at each point of maximal risk: the QALY-lens caveat precedes any number, the geographic table is labeled a by-construction decomposition, the frontier counterfactual is immediately deflated as a marginal comparison with a cited diminishing-returns floor, and the conclusion states the number is a model output under stated priors, not a fact. Low-QALY causes are never disparaged; the treatment of Scott is descriptive and, where evaluative at all, favorable; the EA framing stays on the measurement side of the line; the personal-project disclaimer appears twice. The stance-sweep-plus-browser design operationalizes neutrality by handing the decisive judgment to the reader. Two items must be fixed before posting: a sentence labeling the headline decomposition "the paper's central fact," and the absence of a financial-relationship disclosure. Remaining findings are wording-level.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:2924:paper/review/round1/neutrality.md:25:The four scoping disclaimers at exactly the overreach points; zero prescriptive language; the stance sweep as structural neutrality; evenhanded modeling toward the subject (realization >1 on cited capacity evidence); genuine, specific limitations.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2925-paper/review/sol/methodology.md:3:READ: paper/review/rendered.txt, paper/index.qmd, src/msqaly/model.py, src/msqaly/allocation.py, src/msqaly/distributions.py, src/msqaly/geo.py, data/parameters.yaml, results/summary.md. Run code with .venv/bin/python and pytest if useful.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log-2926-paper/review/sol/methodology.md:5:SCRUTINIZE: (a) the credibility × realization two-discount structure — is "each doubt enters exactly one layer" true of the code; double/under-counting; (b) Dirichlet allocation; means-vs-medians discipline in prose and tables (means-additivity claims); (c) the elasticity regression — selection into disclosure, 990-match survivorship, log-log OLS caveats: does the paper state the right ones; (d) the stance interpolation (floor 0.01 for non-randomized tiers, piecewise linear, 0.5 = tiers as-is) — artifacts, correct description of the RCT-only extreme; (e) QALY conventions (65 remaining years, utility 0.87, 3% discounting) applied consistently; frontier handicapping like-for-like as claimed; (f) the by-construction geographic decomposition — is its scope claim exactly right; (g) benefit-cost at HHS VQALY (ratio-of-medians vs median-of-ratios); (h) Monte Carlo mechanics (seed 0, 100k draws, which statistics are per-draw vs summary).
