paper/review/sol/methodology.log-3537-+   **LOCATION:** `paper/index.qmd` lines 160–193; rendered paper lines 369–379 and Table 2; `src/msqaly/geo.py` lines 220–297.  
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3538:+   **Problem:** The geographic scope claim is substantively correct but should be narrower. The displayed regional QALYs are not geographic outcomes carried through each Monte Carlo draw. The notebook takes each archetype's mean QALYs and deterministically apportions them using a fixed regional dollar matrix. Hence the rows sum by construction conditional on the location equal-split rules, audited fractions, prior reclassification of selected non-U.S. health-relevant dollars into `global_health`, and the assumption of identical effectiveness within each resulting archetype. No geographic, audit, or within-archetype regional uncertainty is represented. “The same run decomposed” can be read more strongly than the code warrants.  
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3539:+   **Concrete fix:** Call Table 2 a deterministic post-estimation decomposition of mean archetype QALYs. State in the caption that no region-level effect or uncertainty is estimated and that geography affects pricing only earlier, when selected non-U.S. dollars are reclassified into the global-health archetype.
