paper/review/sol/citations.log-36-MacKenzie Scott has disclosed $26.39 billion in gifts to more than 2,500 organizations since 2019 — roughly a third of American megagiving in 2025 — yet almost
paper/review/sol/citations.log-37-none of it is denominated in outcomes. This paper prices the entire portfolio in
paper/review/sol/citations.log:38:quality-adjusted life-years. A Monte Carlo model allocates dollars across 14 intervention archetypes using Scott’s own gift-level database, imputes the undisclosed third
paper/review/sol/citations.log-39-from recipients’ pre-gift IRS 990 revenue, assigns each archetype a cost-per-QALY
paper/review/sol/citations.log-40-anchor from published causal estimates, and shrinks every effect toward zero in
paper/review/sol/citations.log-41-proportion to the causal credibility of its evidence. The best-guess estimate is a
paper/review/sol/citations.log-42-median of roughly 202,000 QALYs (90% interval 94,000–419,000), a blended $150,000
paper/review/sol/citations.log-43-per QALY, and a benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 at the U.S. government’s value per QALY.
paper/review/sol/citations.log-44-Three findings follow. First, impact is geographically concentrated: the 4.8% of
paper/review/sol/citations.log:45:dollars funding health and development delivered outside the United States produces
paper/review/sol/citations.log-46-69% of estimated health impact. Second, gift size scales with recipient size to only
paper/review/sol/citations.log-47-the 0.41 power — a 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more money. Third,
paper/review/sol/citations.log-48-the answer is dominated by evidence philosophy rather than arithmetic: restricting to
--
