paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2136-| 1 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The manuscript now says the multipliers are *designed* to partition doubt and explicitly concedes mixed null/positive evidence, omitted harm, and imperfect separation (rendered lines 164–168, 701–716), but it still provides neither the requested archetype-level ledger nor one-factor-off runs. Deferral is defensible for an SSRN working paper because the overlap is now prominent, but it is not a completed audit. |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2137-| 2 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The exact concentration (60), an implied global-health interval, the judgment-prior interpretation, and the omitted pipeline uncertainty are now stated (lines 168–176, 716–718); no concentration sweep, fixed-share case, bootstrap, or hierarchical propagation is reported. Deferral is defensible for a working paper now that the interval is not presented as sampling uncertainty. |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2138-| 3 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The selected sample, sample flow, repeated-gift treatment, pooled years, 287 median fallbacks, and lack of prediction validation are disclosed (lines 104–113), but there is still no clustered/robust inference, held-out validation, influence analysis, or propagation of elasticity/fallback uncertainty. Deferral is defensible only because the fit is now expressly descriptive and conditional; the abstract/contribution language should retain that qualification. |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log:2139:| 4 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The caption gives the exact endpoint means and calls the curve a scenario rather than a bound, and the dominant bucket is correctly attributed (lines 601–615). However, the introduction still says “counting only randomized evidence,” the plotted ticks still say “RCT-only” and “face value,” and the limitations call the sweep an “honest bound” (lines 51–52, 594–604, 701–703). |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2140-| 5 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The false common-convention claim has been replaced by an accurate source-specific account for the default run (lines 177–187). Declining to overwrite source conventions is defensible, but the repository still exposes a general discount-rate setting that rescales only mortality conversions, VQALY, and the frontier while leaving direct cost-per-QALY anchors fixed; that control must be labeled as a partial conversion sensitivity rather than a common discount-rate scenario. |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2141-| 6 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The methods now accurately state a shared realization draw and separate RCT-grade frontier credibility (lines 182–187), and the GiveWell-to-QALY conversion is identified as the model's. Yet the results still say “the same realization and credibility discounts” (lines 562–565), contrary to `src/msqaly/model.py`, which independently draws frontier credibility; raw/realization-only variants also remain absent. |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log:2142:| 7 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | Table 1 now correctly labels its $/QALY as center dollars divided by mean QALYs, a ratio of expectations (lines 218–221). The generated `results/summary.md` still displays nonadditive archetype medians in an ordering based on another statistic without the requested warning, so the artifact-level ambiguity remains. |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2143-| 8 | **RESOLVED** | Table 2 and the surrounding prose now unambiguously identify a deterministic post-estimation decomposition of mean archetype QALYs, with no regional effect or uncertainty estimated and geography affecting pricing only through routing (rendered lines 422–425, 513–516). |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2144-| 9 | **RESOLVED** | The manuscript now defines 4.9 as the median draw-level benefit–cost ratio and states that its 90% interval jointly reflects health-output and sampled HHS valuation uncertainty (lines 193–199). |
paper/review/sol/reproducibility.round2.log-2145-| 10 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The interval is now called a probabilistic-sensitivity range rather than a confidence interval, major omitted inputs are listed, and Monte Carlo error is acknowledged (lines 193–199, 701–723). The requested compact dependence/fixed-input/statistic specification and an actual convergence or Monte Carlo-error calculation are still absent; “a few hundred” is asserted rather than shown. |
