paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log-657-web/params.json:82:      "source": "Populations in the causal mortality studies are low-income adults roughly age 50-64. Remaining life expectancy ~26y is calibrated to [Chetty et al. (2016, JAMA)](https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2513561): bottom-income-quartile life expectancy at 40 is ~78 (men) to ~83 (women), implying mid-20s remaining years around age 55. Utility ~0.78 is calibrated to US EQ-5D population norms (e.g., [Jiang et al. 2021](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11136-020-02650-y), ages 55-64 ~0.80 overall, lower at low income). Discounted at 3% with a half-cycle correction."
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log:658:web/params.json:111:      "source": "Derived from [GiveWell's current impact estimates](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates) of cost per life saved, 2022-2024 program averages: ~$4,000 (Malaria Consortium seasonal chemoprevention) to ~$5,500 (AMF nets), figures GiveWell rounds up to the nearest $500. Treating those as ~2023 dollars and inflating by [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) 335.123/304.702 = 1.10 gives ~$4,400-$6,050 per life. A child death averted at ~age 1 with ~65 remaining life-years, discounted at 3% with half-cycle correction (annuity ~28.9) and utility ~0.87, is ~25.1 discounted QALYs, giving endpoints of ~$175-$241 per QALY-equivalent; the loguniform {150, 260} widens that for conversion uncertainty (utility, remaining years, price level). An earlier revision also used a 2015 AMF figure ($3,340/life, itself already a discounted-QALY-era calculation, in ~2015 dollars); it is retired here in favor of GiveWell's current program averages."
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log-659-web/params.json:173:      "identification": "DD across staggered state Medicaid expansions with linked coverage data (Sommers 2017; Miller, Johnson & Wherry 2021 corroborate with linked administrative mortality for the ACA expansion). Strong; the Oregon HIE RCT (null on 2-yr physical health measures) tempers it, hence not the top tier.",
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log:660:web/params.json:196:      "source": "[Bailey & Goodman-Bacon (2015), AER 105(3)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.20120070) ([full text](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4436657/)) report \"a cost-per-year-of-life ratio of approximately $54,000\" for CHCs in 2012 dollars (Medicare comparison: $161,373-$459,000 per life-year, i.e. CHCs at 1/8 to 1/3 the cost). Inflated with [FRED CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) from the 2012 annual average 229.594 to May 2026 335.123 (x1.460): ~$79k per life-year; the loguniform $55k-$115k places ~\u00b145% around that point estimate. The model divides by the utility-weight draw to convert life-years to QALYs (the prior revision skipped that conversion and used an invented Medicare prior; both fixed here)."
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log:661:web/params.json:211:      "source": "Anchors are 2000s-era nominal ICERs and are inflated here. The [Community Guide review](https://www.thecommunityguide.org/findings/mental-health-and-mental-illness-collaborative-care-management-depressive-disorders.html) reports the Gilbody-era $17k-$39k/QALY range in 2008 dollars, which [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) 335.123/215.303 = 1.56 inflates to ~$26k-$61k; the systematic review at [van Steenbergen-Weijenburg et al. (2010), BMC Health Services Research 10:19](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/1472-6963-10-19) reports study ICERs of ~$21.5k-$49.5k without year normalization (similar-era dollars, similar inflated magnitude; an earlier revision misattributed this link to \"Gilbody et al. 2006\" and pooled the two reviews' endpoints as one range). Together the inflated cost-effective case sits around $26k-$77k. The upper tail extends toward [Grochtdreis et al. (2015)](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0123078), whose healthcare-perspective ICERs reach $153,299 in 2012 international dollars (not CPI-converted here; international dollars are not US CPI dollars). The 5th/95th prior {25k, 150k} brackets the inflated evidence."
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log-662-web/params.json:218:      "identification": "Dollars route here by delivery geography: the non-US share of each organization's reported service locations, applied to its health-relevant focus areas (src/msqaly/allocation.py). The routed portfolio spans GiveWell-grade programs backed by RCTs (Malaria Consortium $10M, Evidence Action $20M, GiveDirectly's global program $50M+$5M) through strong community-health-worker and health-systems organizations (Living Goods $25M+$3.5M, Muso $15M, Amref $50M, Partners In Health $50M, Noora Health $20M, icddr,b $16M) to partial-health-tagged organizations. strong_quasi reflects that mix.",
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log-663-web/params.json:226:      "source": "Pricing a non-US health dollar at US anchors understates it by orders of magnitude \u2014 the correction a reader prompted. The 90% CI $300-$4,000 per QALY (2026$) spans [GiveWell's current program averages](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates) (~$4,000-5,500 per under-5 life saved ~ $175-241 per discounted QALY, the marquee floor sitting just below this range's low end), community-health-worker and systems programs GiveWell scores in the low single-digit multiples of cash (~$500-2,000 per QALY-equivalent), and [GiveDirectly's global cash program](https://blog.givewell.org/2024/11/12/re-evaluating-the-impact-of-unconditional-cash-transfers/) (child-mortality channel ~ $8,000 per discounted QALY, above this range's high end \u2014 the tail covers it). Gift amounts verified in [Yield Giving's database](https://yieldgiving.com/gifts)."
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log:664:web/params.json:271:      "source": "Point anchor: [Holtgrave et al. (2013), AIDS and Behavior 17(5)](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10461-012-0204-3) report $62,493/QALY for the Housing & Health intervention \u2014 an HIV-positive, unstably-housed cohort (2004-2008 study), NOT general chronic homelessness. The team's [underlying cost analysis](https://shnny.org/uploads/Cost_and_Threshold_Analysis_of_Housing_as_an_HIV_Prevention.pdf) is stated in 2005 dollars; inflating by [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) 335.123/195.267 = 1.716 gives ~$107k/QALY (an earlier revision assumed 2008 dollars, ~$97k). The {30k, 220k} prior brackets that with room for cheaper high-need PSH cases (frequent cost offsets) and costlier general populations. [NASEM (2018)](https://nap.nationalacademies.org/read/25133/chapter/6) is cited for the mixed-evidence assessment only."
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log-665-web/allocation_v10.json:4: "description": "The allocation as published with the July 13 geographic-routing correction: every 'global'-listed organization treated as fully non-US. Preserved for comparison; superseded by v1.1.",
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log:666:paper/index.qmd:136:The coarsest geographic field is the bare label "global." An audit of the 50 organizations with the most dollars attached to that label — 87% of its dollars; 20 of the 50 also list other locations — replaced the blanket assumption of fully-abroad delivery with fractions coded independently by two model families from each organization's filings and program reports, then reconciled — the second coder confirmed 33 within tolerance and disputed 17; four disputes were adjudicated to documented filings arithmetic, and final fractions average the two coders everywhere else, with per-organization sources and confidence grades — 16 high, 17 medium, 17 low — committed to the repository. Many "global" organizations operate substantially in the United States: Planned Parenthood and Crisis Text Line, for example, list "global" service but are roughly 95% and 93% U.S. in their most recent organization-wide reporting — later-period proxies for how earlier gifts were deployed, since neither reports gift-level allocation. The audited allocation routes `{python} F["abroad_share"]` of the ledger to the global health and development archetype. That routed bucket is itself mixed: its dollars sit `{python} F["gh_ssa"]` in Sub-Saharan Africa, `{python} F["gh_sasia"]` in South Asia, and `{python} F["gh_latam"]` in Latin America, but `{python} F["gh_unattrib"]` is unattributable multi-region activity and roughly `{python} F["gh_hic"]` sits in Europe & Central Asia plus Canada — regions that are not classified by income here, so the bucket's true high-income share is unidentified — all priced at the same low-and-middle-income anchors, a coarseness the limitations section flags.
paper/review/sol/redteam.round3.log:667:paper/index.qmd:311:The credibility tiers and realization distribution are judgment priors with no literature calibration; the ordering is defensible, the levels are not measured, and the stance sweep is the honest bound on their influence. The QALY lens counts only health, so the estimate is a partial accounting that omits both the non-health benefits where Scott concentrates — education, mobility, equity — and any possible harms; it is not a floor on total wellbeing. Credibility shrinks toward zero but never below it, so the model places no mass on harmful giving; the closest available zero scenario is the near-RCT-only stance floor, which drives unsupported archetypes to ~1% credit. Allocation splits each organization's dollars equally across its focus areas and service locations; both are coarse, and the geography audit covers only the 50 largest "global"-listed organizations. Realization is one global draw, so it cannot vary by cause. Archetype anchors treat heterogeneous organizations as draws from one distribution. Within each cause, delivery regions are priced identically, so the geographic decomposition exposes assumptions rather than measuring regional differences. The undisclosed third of dollars is imputed from a fitted elasticity, not observed. The routed global-health bucket prices its unattributable and high-income-region dollars — roughly a fifth of the bucket — at low-and-middle-income anchors, an upward-bias channel. Several cost priors average over mixed null-and-positive evidence before the credibility discount applies, so the two-multiplier separation of doubts is imperfect at those boundaries. The Dirichlet allocation spread is a subjective prior; uncertainty from the elasticity fit, unmatched filings, the focus-area crosswalk, and the geography audit is not propagated. Allocation shares are derived in nominal dollars and applied to the real total; re-deriving in real dollars moves shares by hundredths of a percentage point. The geography audit's scalar U.S. shares and regional decompositions were reconciled separately and can differ by fractions of a point per organization. Finally, several anchors rest on a small number of quasi-experimental papers whose external validity to Scott's grantees is exactly what the realization factor is guessing at.
